>[Question]
>Two guys are walking down the street.  The first one asks the second 
>if he has any kids.  The second guy syas, "I have 3 kids."  The first 
>guy asks, "How old are they?"  The second guy says, "The product of 
>thier ages is 36."  The first guy thinks about it for a while and 
>says, "That's not enough, I need another clue."  The second guy 
>says, "The sum of their ages is the number of that building across 
>the street."  The first guy thinks about it again and after a while 
>says, "I still need another clue."  The second guy says, "The oldest 
>one has a red hair."  The first guys says, "I've got it!"  How old 
>are the kids?
>
>[Difficulty]
>I think there are not enough clues in the problem.  I can't think of 
>how the sum of the number of the building (which they did not 
>specifically state) and the color of the hair help in any way.
>
>[Thoughts]
>36 = (x) (x+__) (x+__)  I need two numbers to fill the blank space.  
>since I do not have a real equation, I am just doing a trial-and-
>error method.  I have come up with 2,3 and 6 for the ages of the 
>kids.  I can't come up with a real solution so i need one.  Please 
>help me!  Thanks.

